value.value: A benign tumor usually arising in the face, trunk or thighs.
A benign epithelial neoplasm occurring in the head, neck or back region. It is characterized by proliferation of basaloid cells in the upper dermis with broad attachments to the epidermis.
A benign neoplasm characterized by sebaceous cell differentiation. It arises from the dermis and typically affects the face and neck.
An epithelial cell that produces sebum, a thick, semi-fluid substance composed of fat and epithelial debris from the cells of innermost layer of the epithelium.

A rare condition characterized by diffuse spread of sarcoma cells throughout the meninges. The neoplastic cells are derived from meningeal connective tissue. Clinically, this disorder may present as a fulminant pachymeningitis and/or encephalitis.
A carcinoma that arises from the sebaceous glands of the ocular adnexa and sebaceous glands of the eyelid and caruncle.
A rare variant of sebaceous carcinoma that does not affect the ocular region.

A slow-growing, usually solitary, dome-shaped benign sweat gland adenoma, most frequently located on the eyelid.  It is characterized by a cystic proliferation of apocrine glands. Surgical excision is curative.
A carcinoma that arises in a cylindroma.
A very rare eccrine adenocarcinoma characterized by the presence of prominent ductal differentiation.

label.value: Ductal Eccrine Carcinoma with Spindle Cell Elements

value.value: A variant of ductal eccrine carcinoma with spindled cell appearance.
A variant of ductal eccrine carcinoma with squamoid metaplasia.

label.value: Ductal Eccrine Carcinoma with Abundant Fibromyxoid Stroma

value.value: A variant of ductal eccrine carcinoma with abundant fibromyxoid stroma.
A malignant peripheral nerve sheath tumor which shows rhabdomyosarcomatous differentiation. More than half of the patients have neurofibromatosis type 1. The prognosis is usually poor.
A cylindroma occurring as a solitary sporadic lesion.

A rare autosomal dominant genodermatosis associated with germline mutations of the CYLD tumor suppressor gene. It is characterized by the development of multiple adnexal tumors (usually cylindromas and trichoepitheliomas), typically in the skin of the scalp. It manifests with numerous papules and/or large dome-shaped nodules on the scalp, resembling a turban.
A poroma characterized by the presence of cords and aggregates of neoplastic cells in the superficial dermis in connection with the epidermis.
A rare intraepidermal neoplasia that arises from the acrosyringial portion of the eccrine duct.

A rare benign eccrine lesion usually arising on acral areas as a solitary papule or nodule. Multiple lesions are referred as syringofibroadenomatosis. It is characterized by the presence of epithelial cuboidal cells forming anastomosing cords in a fibrovascular stroma.
The act of working out the form of something (as by making a sketch or outline or plan) or the result of this activity.
Any number of entities (members) considered as a unit.

An uncommon granular cell tumor which may metastasize to other anatomic sites. Morphologic characteristics include the presence of spindling neoplastic cells, necrosis, extensive pleomorphism, prominent nucleoli, and increased mitiotic activity.
The act of making something (a product) from raw materials.
A machine-readable representation of information in a visual format on a surface.
The lower opening of the digestive tract, lying in the cleft between the buttocks, through which fecal matter is extruded.
A substance formed by chemical union of two or more elements or ingredients in definite proportion by weight.
A feeling of trust (in someone or something).

A person who edits material for publication; a person having managerial and sometimes policy-making responsibility for the editorial part of a publishing firm or of a newspaper, magazine, or other publication; the supervisor or conductor of a department of a newspaper, magazine, etc.
A discrepancy between a computed, observed, or measured value or condition and the true, specified, or theoretically correct value or condition.

A non-Hodgkin lymphoma composed of small to medium sized B-lymphocytes (centrocytes). Most patients present with advanced stage disease with lymphadenopathy, hepatosplenomegaly, and bone marrow involvement. The gastrointestinal tract is the most commonly affected extranodal site by this type of non-Hodgkin lymphoma. The vast majority of cases express the t(11;14)(q13;q32) resulting in the rearrangement of the BCL-1 gene and the overexpression of cyclin D1 mRNA.
A characteristic or attribute of an object, event, or other entity under observation that can assume more than one value and by which a classification can be assigned.

An atypical proliferation of atypical melanocytes in the dermal-epidermal junction, without infiltration of the papillary or reticular dermis. The melanocytic proliferation is associated with actinic damage and epidermal atrophy.  It usually occurs in the sun-exposed skin of elderly people.  It is a form of melanoma in situ.
A secretory cell that discharges its product without loss of cytoplasm.
A glandular secreting cell in which the apical portion of the secreting cell is cast off along with the secretory products that have accumulated therein.
A change in the nucleotide sequence of the CDC73 gene.
Natural substances derived from living organisms such as cells, tissues, proteins, and DNA.
A flat dish with multiple individual wells that are arrayed in a standardized number, size, and arrangement.
An arrangement of objects side by side in a line.
An arrangement of objects one under another in a line.
A BioSequence is an object representation of a DNA, RNA, or protein sequence.  It can be represented by a Clone, Gene, or the sequence. (caMAGE)
An item inserted in a written or electronic record.
A detectable physical quantity or impulse (e.g., voltage, current, or magnetic field strength).
A style or design of an item.
